<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="chap-measure-space">
<title>Measure Spaces</title>
<introduction>
<blockquote>
<p><q>It is frequently claimed that Lebesgue integration is as easy to teach as Riemann integration. This is probably true, but I have yet to be convinced that it is as easy to learn.</q></p>
<attribution>
<p>T.W. Körner</p>
</attribution>
</blockquote>
</introduction>
<section>
<title>Measure spaces</title>
<p>There will be a scarcity of examples in this section. In Section~\ref{sec: construction} we will develop tools to construct measures. After that, we will have access to a plethora of examples. Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set. A measure will assign a non-negative value to subsets of <m>X</m>, but not necessarily all subsets. We need the following definition(s) to describe the domain of a measure.</p>
<definition xml:id="def-sigma-alg">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m> be the power set of <m>X</m>.
A collection of sets <m>\mathcal{M} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> is a <em><m>\sigma</m>-algebra</em><fn>The suffix `<m>\sigma</m>-' is usually used to denote a countably infinite version of whatever word comes after the `<m>\sigma</m>-'. 
With that information you can probably infer what an <em>algebra of sets</em> is.</fn> if</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\emptyset \in \mathcal{M}</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> then <m>A^c = X\backslash A \in \mathcal{M}</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>, then <m>\bigcup_{n=1}^\infty A_n \in \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</definition>
<definition xml:id="def-measurable-space">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>\mathcal{M}</m> be a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of subsets of <m>X</m>.
The pair <m>(X, \mathcal{M})</m> is called a <em>measurable space</em>.<idx><h>measurable space</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p>We record some basic properties of <m>\sigma</m>-algebras which we will need frequently.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-sigma-alg-props">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> be a measurable space. Then</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>X \in \mathcal{M}</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under countable intersections, i.e. if <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> then
        <md>\bigcap_{n=1}^\infty A_n \in \mathcal{M};</md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under finite unions and finite intersections;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>A,B \in \mathcal{M}</m> then <m>A\backslash B \in M</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>SInce <m>\emptyset^c = X</m>, it follows from conditions (i) and (ii) of <xref ref="def-sigma-alg" text="Definition"/>, that <m>X \in \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
<p>Let <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
Then, it follows from conditions (ii) and (iii) of <xref ref="def-sigma-alg" text="Definition"/>  the <m>\bigcup_n A_n^c \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
Using De Morgan's Identity, and condition (ii) again, we have</p>
<md> \bigcap_{n=1}^\infty A_n = X \left[\backslash \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty A_n^c\right] \in \mathcal{M}.</md>
<p>Suppose <m>A_1, \ldots, A_k</m> is a finite collection of sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>. For <m>n &gt;k</m>, let <m>A_n = \emptyset</m>.
Then, by condition (i) of Defintion~\ref{def: sigma-alg}, <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of subsets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
By condition (iii),</p>
<md> \bigcup_{n=1}^k A_n = \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty A_n \in \mathcal{M}.</md>
<p>Thus <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is also closed under finite unions.
Similarly, we can show that <m>\bigcap_{n=1}^k A_n \in \mathcal{M}</m>.</p>
<p>Finally, take <m>A, B \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
Note</p>
<md> A\backslash B = A \cap B^c.</md>
<p>As <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under complements and finite intersections, it follows that <m>A \backslash B</m>.</p>
</proof>
<example xml:id="exam-P-X-measurable-space">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m> be the power-set of subsets of <m>X</m>.
Then <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra, and thus <m>(X, \mathcal{P}(X))</m> is a measurable space.</p>
</example>
<p>There are occasions when we will consider measurable spaces of the form <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X))</m>, (particularly if <m>X</m> is countable). However, in most cases we will consider <m>\sigma</m>-algebras which are strictly contained in <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m>.</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop-gen-sig-alg">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set. 
Let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a non-empty collection of sets. Then there is a unique <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{M}</m> such that <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{M}</m>, and if <m>\mathcal{N}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra containing <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, then <m>\mathcal{M} \subseteq \mathcal{N}</m>.</p>
<p>That is, there is a unique smallest <m>\sigma</m>-algebra containing <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</p>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>Z</m> be the collection of all <m>\sigma</m>-algebras of <m>X</m> that contain <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
Note that <m>Z</m> is non-empty, as <m>\mathcal{P}(X) \in Z</m>. 
Let</p>
<md> \mathcal{M} = \bigcap_{\mathcal{N} \in Z} \mathcal{N}. </md>
<p>That <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra with the desired properties follows readily.</p>
</proof>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}</m> be a non-empty collection of subsets of <m>X</m>.
Let <m>\mathcal{M}</m> be the unique, smallest <m>\sigma</m>-algebra containing <m>\mathcal{S}</m> (in the sense of <xref ref="prop-gen-sig-alg" text="Proposition"/>).
We call <m>\mathcal{M}</m> the <em><m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.</em></p>
</definition>
<definition xml:id="exam-Borel-sets">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
Denote by <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m> the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the open sets in <m>X</m>.
We call <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m> the <em>Borel sets of <m>X</m></em>.<idx><h>Borel sets</h></idx>
If <m>A \in \mathcal{B}(X)</m> we say that <m>A</m> is a <em>Borel set in X</em>.</p>
<p>When <m>X = \mathbb{R}</m>, we will denote the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}(\mathbb{R})</m> by <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.</p>
</definition>
<remark>
<p>Recall that every open set <m>\mathcal{U} \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is a countable union of open intervals.
Thus, the open sets in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> are in the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the open intervals.
Hence, the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra generated by the open intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</remark>
<p>We will now (finally) give the definition of a measure and a measure space.</p>
<definition xml:id="def-measure">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> be a measure space.
A function <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{M} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> is a <em>measure</em><idx><h>measure</h></idx> on <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m> if</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\mu(\emptyset) = 0</m>; and</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of disjoint sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m> then
<md> \mu\left( \bigcup_{n=1}^\infty A_n \right) = \sum_{n=1}^\infty \mu(A_n).</md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>If <m>\mu</m> is a measure on a measurable space <m>(X,\mathcal{M})</m>, we call the triple <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> a <em>measure space</em>.
<idx><h>measure space</h></idx>
The sets <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> are called <em>measurable sets</em><idx><h>measurable set</h></idx> in the measure space <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m>.</p>
</definition>
<remark>
<p>A function which satisfies condition (ii) in <xref ref="def-measure" text="Definition"/> is said to be <em>countable additive on disjoint sets</em><idx><h>countable additivity</h></idx>.
This property is frequently abbreviated to simply <em>`countably additive'</em>.
We must be careful to remember that countable additivity only applies to <em>disjoint</em> sets.</p>
</remark>
<p>The condition of countable additivity implies finite additivity. If <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> is a finite collection of disjoint sets in a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{M}</m>, we can extend <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> to a countably infinite collection <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> by letting <m>A_k = \emptyset</m> for <m>k&gt;n</m>, as we did in <xref ref="prop-sigma-alg-props" text="Proposition"/>. Then, we have</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^n\right) &amp;= \mu\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^\infty\right) \\
    &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(A_k) \\
    &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^n \mu(A_k).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Note that the definition of a measure does not assume that <m>\mu</m> only takes finite values, i.e. <m>\mu(A) = \infty</m> is an allowed value, and there is no assumption that the series in condition (ii) of <xref ref="def-measure" text="Definition"/> are convergent. We use the usual rules of addition with <m>\infty</m> and <m>- \infty</m>:</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\infty + x &amp;= \infty, \text{ for all }x \in \mathbb{R};\\
    -\infty + x &amp;= -\infty, \text{ for all }x \in \mathbb{R};\\
    \infty + \infty &amp;= \infty; \text{ and}\\
    -\infty + (-\infty) &amp;= -\infty.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>However, we must be careful to avoid <m>-\infty + \infty</m>, as <m>-\infty + \infty</m> is undefined.</p>
<definition>
<p><idx><h>measure space</h><h sortby="sigma-finite"><m>\sigma</m>-finite</h></idx>
A measure space <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite if there is a countable collection of sets <m>\{A_n\}_{n=1}^\infty</m> in <m>\mathcal{M}</m> such that</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\mu(A_n)&lt; \infty</m> for each <m>n</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>X = \bigcup_n^\infty A_n.</m></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>If <m>\mu(X) &lt; \infty</m> then <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a <em>finite measure space</em>.<idx><h>measure space</h><h>finite</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<definition>
<p>A measure space <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is <em>complete</em> if, for each <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> with <m>\mu(A) = \emptyset</m>, if <m>B \subseteq A</m> then <m>B \in \mathcal{M}</m>.<idx><h>measure space</h><h>complete</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<remark>
<p>We will pause here to assess where we are going. 
    One of our main motivations for developing measure theory, as discussed in Sections~\ref{sec: intro ftoc}~and~\ref{sec: int lim swap}, is to develop a theory of integration on the real line that is more robust than Riemann integration.</p>
<p>For an interval <m>I \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> let <m>\ell(I)</m> denote the length of <m>I</m>.
    To form a Riemann sum for a function <m>f</m>, we partition an interval <m>[a,b]</m> into subintervals</p>
<md> [a,b] = I_1 \cup \ldots\cup I_n </md>
<p>and the Riemann sum is given by</p>
<md> \sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i^*) \ell(I_i)</md>
<p>where <m>x_i^*</m> is some element of <m>I_i</m>.</p>
<p>The main idea of Lebesgue integration is to define a measure <m>m</m> on (a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of) subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, so that <m>m(I) = \ell(I)</m> for intervals <m>I</m>.
    With <m>m</m> in hand, we can then decompose <m>[a,b]</m> using sets other than intervals.
    I.e., the idea is to use, instead of just Riemann sums, sums of the form</p>
<md> \sum_{i=1}^n f(x_i^*) m(E_i)</md>
<p>where <m>x_i^* \in E_i</m>, and <m>\{E_i\}_{i=1}^n</m> is a disjoint collection of measurable sets such that <m>\bigcup_{i=1}^n E_i = [a,b]</m>.
    Broadening the scope of the sets we can `measure', i.e. using <m>m</m> to measure sets that are not necessarily intervals, we will develop a theory of integration stronger than Riemann integration.</p>
<p>The exact definition of <m>m</m>, and the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra <m>\mathcal{M}</m> it acts on, will have to wait until we have some more tools in our belt.
    We can see now, however, that if <m>m</m> is to do what we want it to do, then <m>\mathcal{M}</m> will have to contain all intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> (and hence <m>\mathcal{M}</m> will have to contain all the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}</m>).</p>
</remark>
<example xml:id="exam-counting">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be any non-empty set and let <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m> be the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of all subsets of <m>X</m>.
Define <m>c \colon \mathcal{P}(X) \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> by</p>
<md> c(A) = \infty</md>
<p>if <m>A</m> contains infinitely many elements, and <m>c(A) = n</m> if <m>A</m> has <m>n</m> elements, for <m>n</m> finite.
Then <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X),c)</m> is a measure space. 
We call <m>c</m> the <em>counting measure</em> on <m>X</m>.<idx><h>measure</h><h>counting measure</h></idx></p>
<p>The measure space <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X),c)</m> is always complete; it is <m>\sigma</m>-finite if and only if <m>X</m> is countable; it is finite if and only if <m>X</m> is finite.</p>
</example>
<example xml:id="exam-dirac-measure">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{F})</m> be a measurable space.
Fix <m>x \in X</m>.
Define <m>\delta_x</m> on <m>\mathcal{F}</m> by <idx><h>measure</h><h>Dirac measure</h></idx></p>
<md>
\delta_x(A) = \begin{cases} 1 &amp;\text{if }x \in A\\ 0 &amp;\text{if }x \notin A\end{cases}.
</md>
<p>Then <m>\delta_x</m> is a measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{F})</m> called the <em>Dirac measure at <m>x</m></em>.<idx><h>measure</h><h>Dirac measure</h></idx></p>
</example>
<definition xml:id="def-borel-meas">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
A measure <m>\mu</m> on the Borel sets <m>\mathcal{B}(X)</m> is a <em>Borel measure</em><idx><h>Borel measure</h></idx> if
<m>\mu(K) &lt; \infty</m> 
for all compact subsets <m>K \subseteq X</m>.</p>
</definition>
<p>We will rarely want to define a measure on a set which does not have some natural topology on it. Indeed, most examples of measures that we will see will be Borel measures. The Dirac measure of <xref ref="exam-dirac-measure" text="Example"/> is Borel measure when <m>X</m> is a topological space and <m>\mathcal{F} = \mathcal{B}(X)</m> is the Borel sets (see <xref ref="exer-dirac-meas" text="Exercise"/>). Even the counting measure of <xref ref="exam-counting" text="Example"/> is a Borel measure if we endow <m>X</m> with the discrete topology (see <xref ref="exer-counting-Borel" text="Exercise"/>).</p>
<p>Probability theory can be naturally described in terms of measure theory. Probability theory is a subject in its own right and has led to some differences in naming and notation conventions.</p>
<definition>
<p>A <em>probability space</em><idx><h>probability space</h></idx><idx><h>sample space</h><see>probability space</see></idx> is a finite measure space <m>(\Omega, \mathcal{F}, P)</m> where <m>P(\Omega) = 1</m>.
The measure <m>P</m> is called a <em>probability measure</em>. <idx><h>measure</h><h>probability measure</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p>We will forgo any further direct mention of probabilty theory until later,</p>
<p>though it has had an influence on some of the theory we will see along the way.</p>
<p>We end this section with an important piece of verbiage.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{F},\mu)</m> be a measure space.
    A property <m>P</m> is said to hold for <em>almost all <m>x\in X</m></em><idx><h>almost all</h></idx> (abbreviated as <em>a.a.</em> <m>x \in X</m>)<idx><h>a.a.</h><see>almost all</see></idx> or <em>almost everywhere</em><idx><h>almost everywhere</h></idx> (abbreviate <em>e.e.</em>)<idx><h>a.e.</h><see>almost everywhere</see></idx> if there is a measurable set <m>E \subseteq X</m> with <m>\mu(E) = 0</m> such that <m>P</m> holds on <m>X \backslash E</m>.</p>
</definition>
</section>
<section>
<title>Properties of measures</title>
<proposition xml:id="prop-measure-properties">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space.
Then the following hold</p>
<ol>
<li><p>(Monotonicity) If <m>A, B \in \mathcal{M}</m> with <m>B \subseteq A</m>, then <m>\mu(B)\leq \mu(A)</m>;<idx><h>measure</h><h>monotonicity</h></idx></p>
</li>
<li><p>(Excision) If <m>A,B \in \mathcal{M}</m> with <m>B\subseteq A</m> and <m>\mu(A)&lt;\infty</m>, then <m>\mu(A \backslash B) = \mu(A) - \mu(B)</m>;<idx><h>measure</h><h>excision property</h></idx></p>
</li>
<li><p>(Countable monotonicity) If <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of measurable sets, and <m>E</m> is a measurable set such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k</m>, then <m>\mu(E) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k).</m><idx><h>measure</h><h>countable monotonicity</h></idx></p>
</li>
</ol>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>Take <m>A, B \in \mathcal{M}</m> with <m>B \subseteq A</m>.
Note we can write <m>A</m> as a disjoint union</p>
<md> A = B \cup (A \backslash B).</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md number="yes" xml:id="eq-excision">
\mu(A) = \mu(B) + \mu(A \backslash B).
</md>
<p>Thus, <m>\mu(B) \leq \mu(A)</m>.
If <m>\mu(A)&lt;\infty</m>, then it follows that <m>\mu(B) &lt; \infty</m> and <m>\mu(A\backslash B) &lt; \infty</m>.
Hence, it follows from  <xref ref="eq-excision" text="Equation"/> that</p>
<md> \mu(A\backslash B) = \mu(A) - \mu(B).&lt;fn&gt;That <m>\mu(A)</m> is finite is imporant here. Otherwise we could be looking at <m>\infty - \infty</m>, which is undefined.&lt;/fn&gt;</md>
<p>Now let <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a countable collection of sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
Let <m>A_1 = E_1</m>. 
Let <m>A_2 = E_2 \backslash A_1</m>.
Continuing in this way, we let</p>
<md> A_k = E_k \backslash \bigcup_{n=1}^{k-1} A_n.</md>
<p>In this way, we get a countable family <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> of disjoint measurable sets, which satisfies</p>
<md> \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty A_k = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k,</md>
<p>and <m>\mu(A_k) \leq \mu(E_k)</m> for each <m>k</m>.
Thus, if <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_k E_k</m> we have</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu(E) &amp;\leq \mu\left( \bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k \right) \\
    &amp;= \mu\left( \bigcup_{k=1}^n A_k \right) \\
    &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(A_k) \\
    &amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k).\qedhere
\end{aligned}
</md>
</proof>
<p>The next theorem is called <em>the continuity of measure</em>.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-continuity-of-measure">
<title>Continuity of measure</title>
<p><idx><h>measure</h><h>continuity</h></idx>
Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>If <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of measurable sets satisfying <m>A_k \subseteq A_{k+1}</m> (i.e. <m>\{A_k\}_k</m> ascending measurable sets), then
<md> \mu\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^\infty A_k \right) = \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} \mu(A_k).</md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>If <m>\{B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of measurable sets satisfying <m>B_{k+1} \subseteq B_{k}</m> (i.e. <m>\{B_k\}_k</m> descending measurable sets) and <m>\mu(B_1)&lt;\infty</m>, then
<md> \mu\left(\bigcap_{k=1}^\infty B_k \right) = \lim_{k\rightarrow \infty} \mu(B_k).</md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Let <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be an countable collection of ascending measurable sets, and let <m>A = \bigcup_k A_k</m>.
    If <m>\mu(A_{k_0}) = \infty</m> for some index <m>k_0</m>, then <m>\mu(A) = \infty</m> since <m>A_{k_0} \subseteq A</m> (by the monotonicity of <m>\mu</m>).
    Hence</p>
<md> \infty = \mu(A) = \mu(A_{k_0}) = \lim_k \mu(A_k).</md>
<p>Assume now that <m>\mu(A_k) &lt; \infty</m> for all <m>k</m>.
    Let <m>B_1 = A_1</m>  and let</p>
<md>B_k = A_k \backslash A_{k-1}.</md>
<p>Then <m>\{B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of disjoint measurable sets satisfying</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
A_k = \bigcup_{m=1}^k B_m.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>A</m> is the disjoint union <m>A = \bigcup_k B_k</m>.
    Thus</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\lim_{k} \mu(A_k) &amp;= \lim_k \mu\left(\bigcup_{m=1}^k B_k\right) \\
        &amp;= \lim_k \sum_{m=1}^k \mu(B_m) \\
        &amp;= \sum_{m=1}^\infty \mu(B_m)\\
        &amp;= \mu(A).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus (i) holds.</p>
<p>Now assume <m>\{B_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a descending collection of measurable sets, with <m>\mu(B_1)&lt;\infty</m>.
    For each <m>k</m>, let <m>D_k = B_1 \backslash B_k</m>.
    Then <m>\{D_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is an ascending sequence of measurable sets.
    By part (i), we have that</p>
<md number="yes" xml:id="eq-cont-meas-1">
\mu\left( \bigcup_k D_k \right) = \lim_k \mu(D_k) = \lim_k [\mu(B_1) - \mu(B_k)] = \mu(B_1) - \lim_k \mu(B_k).
</md>
<p>Note that we have used the fact that <m>\mu(B_1)&lt;\infty</m> in order to use the excision property in  <xref ref="eq-cont-meas-1" text="Equation"/>.
    By De Morgan's identities</p>
<md> \bigcup_k D_k = \bigcup_k (B_1 \backslash B_k) = B_1 \backslash \bigcap_k B_k. </md>
<p>Hence</p>
<md number="yes" xml:id="eq-cont-meas-2">
\mu\left(\bigcup_k D_k\right) = \mu(B_1) - \mu\left(\bigcap_k B_k \right).
</md>
<p>Combining  <xref ref="eq-cont-meas-1" text="Equation"/> and  <xref ref="eq-cont-meas-2" text="Equation"/> we get</p>
<md> \mu \left(\bigcap_k B_k \right) = \lim_k \mu(B_k).\qedhere</md>
</proof>
<p>Not all measure spaces that we encounter will be complete. Indeed, we will see that Borel measures need not be complete. We will see an important example of this in the real line later.</p>
<p>However, the next theorem shows that a measure space that is not complete can always be extended to be complete.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-completion-of-meas-space">
<p><idx><h>measure space</h><h>completion</h></idx>
Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space.
Define <m>\mathcal{M}_0</m> to be the collection of subset of <m>X</m></p>
<md> \mathcal{M}_0 = \{A \cup B \colon A \in \mathcal{M},\ B \subseteq C\text{ for some }C \in \mathcal{M} \text{ with }\mu(C) = 0\}.</md>
<p>For <m>E = A \cup B</m> in <m>\mathcal{M}_0</m> where <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m> and <m>B \subseteq C\in \mathcal{M}</m> with <m>\mu(C)=0</m>, define <m>\mu_0(A\cup B) = \mu(A)</m>.
Then <m>\mathcal{M}_0</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra and <m>(X,\mathcal{M}_0,\mu_0)</m> is a complete measure space.<idx><h>measure space</h><h>complete</h></idx></p>
</theorem>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> be a measure space, and let <m>(X,\mathcal{M}_0,\mu_0)</m> be the complete measure space constructed from <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> in <xref ref="thm-completion-of-meas-space" text="Theorem"/>.
Then <m>(X,\mathcal{M}_0,\mu_0)</m> is the <em>completion</em> of <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m>.<idx><h>measure space</h><h>completion</h></idx></p>
</definition>
</section>
<section xml:id="sec-construction">
<title>Constructing measures</title>
<p>The reason for the dearth of examples of measures thus far is simple: measures are complicated. Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M}, \mu)</m> be a measure space. Given <m>A \subseteq X</m> one may ask</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Is <m>A</m> measurable? That is, is <m>A \in \mathcal{M}</m>?</p>
</li>
<li><p>If <m>A</m> is measurable, what is the value of <m>\mu(A)</m>?</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>In general, neither of these questions are easy to answer. However, as we will see, we can make do without having a full answer to these questions. More commonly, we will want <m>\mu</m> to take some prescribed values on a subset <m>\mathcal{S}</m> of <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m>, where <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is not necessarily a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra. In this section we will see how to construct a measure by defining <m>\mu</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> (when <m>\mu</m> and <m>\mathcal{S}</m> are sufficiently well behaved).</p>
<p>The process for constructing measures will involve several steps. Starting with a function <m>\mu</m> on a set of sets <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> we will construct a function <m>\mu^*</m>, called an <em>outer measure</em>, on all of <m>\mathcal{P}(X)</m>. We will then restrict <m>\mu^*</m> two a smaller <m>\sigma</m>-algebra on which it is a measure.</p>
<p>We begin with the definition of an outer measure.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set.
    A function</p>
<md> \mu^* \colon \mathcal{P}(X) \rightarrow [0,\infty]</md>
<p>is an <em>outer measure</em><idx><h>outer measure</h></idx> on <m>X</m> if</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\mu^*(\emptyset) = 0</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of subsets of <m>X</m>, and <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_k E_k</m> then
        <md> \mu^*(E) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(E_k).</md>
<p>I.e. <m>\mu^*</m> is <em>countably monotone.</em><idx><h>countably monotone</h></idx></p>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</definition>
<p>Outer measures are not as well behaved as measures. However, they have two significant advantages: they are defined on all subsets of <m>X</m>, and they are easy to construct.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-outer-measure">
<p><idx><h>outer measure</h><h>induced</h></idx>
  Let <m>X</m> be a nonempty set, let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a non-empty collection of subsets of <m>X</m>, and let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> be any function.
  Define a function <m>\mu^* \colon \mathcal{P}(X) \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> by</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\mu^*(\emptyset) = 0</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\emptyset\neq A</m>, and there exists a countable collection <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> such that <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_k E_k</m>, then
       <md> \mu^*(A) = \inf \left\{ \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k) \colon \{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty \subseteq \mathcal{S},\ A \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k \right\}; </md>
</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\emptyset \neq A</m> and <m>A</m> can not be covered by a countably infinite family in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, then <m>\mu^*(A) = \infty.</m></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Then <m>\mu^*</m> is an outer measure on <m>X</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>By definition, <m>\mu^*(\emptyset) = 0</m>, so we only need to show that <m>\mu^*</m> is countably monotone.
    Take subsets <m>A</m>, and <m>\{A_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> of <m>X</m> with <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_k A_k</m>.
    If <m>\mu^*(A_{k_0}) = \infty</m> for some <m>k_0</m>, then</p>
<md> \mu^*(A) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(A_k) = \infty.</md>
<p>Suppose now that <m>\mu^*(A_k)&lt;\infty</m> for all <m>k</m>.
    Fix <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>. For each <m>k</m>, choose a countable collection <m>\{E_{k,m}\}_{m=1}^\infty</m> of subsets of <m>\mathcal{S}</m> such that</p>
<md> \mu^*(A_k) &gt; \sum_{m=1}^\infty \mu(E_{k,m}) - \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}.</md>
<p>Since <m>A \subseteq \bigcup_k A_k</m>, the collection <m>\{E_{k,m}\}_{k,m=1}^\infty</m> covers <m>A</m>.
    Thus</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A) &amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \sum_{m=1}^\infty \mu(E_{k,m}) \\
        &amp;&lt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty [\mu^*(A_k) + \frac{\varepsilon}{2^k}]\\
        &amp;=  \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(A_k) + \varepsilon.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu^*(A) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(A_k)</m>, and so <m>\mu^*</m> is countably monotone.</p>
</proof>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, and let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a non-empty collection of subsets.
    Let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> be a function and let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure constructed in <xref ref="thm-outer-measure" text="Theorem"/>.
    We call <m>\mu^*</m> the <em>outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m></em>. <idx><h>outer measure</h><h>induced</h></idx></p>
</definition>
<p>Let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure induced from a set function <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty].</m> In general, there is no reason to expect <m>\mu^*</m> to be well-behaved, beyond being an outer measure. We may not even have <m>\mu^*(A) = \mu(A)</m> for <m>A \in \mathcal{S}</m>. We will see that whether or not <m>\mu^*</m> preserves nice properties of <m>\mu</m> (if there are any) will depend on both <m>\mu</m> <em>and</em> <m>\mathcal{S}</m>. The following two examples give instances when the induced outer measure does end up being useful.</p>
<example xml:id="ex-induced-counting-outer-measure">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be an infinite set, and let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all finite subsets of <m>X</m>.
    Let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty)</m> be the counting function.
    I.e. for <m>A \subseteq \mathcal{S}</m>, <m>\mu(A)</m> is the (necessarily finite) number of elements of <m>A</m>.
    If <m>\mu^*</m> is the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>, then <m>\mu^*=c</m> is the counting measure (<xref ref="exer-induced-counting-outer-measure" text="Exercise"/>).</p>
</example>
<example xml:id="ex-induced-length-outer-measure">
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all open intervals in the real line.
    Let <m>\mu</m> be the length function on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, i.e. <m>\mu(I) = \ell(I)</m> for all <m>I \in \mathcal{S}</m>.
    Let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>. 
    Then <m>\mu^*(I) = \ell(I)</m> for all intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> (Exercised~\ref{exer: induced length outer measure}).
    The outer measure <m>\mu^*</m> is called the <em>Lebesgue outer measure on <m>\mathbb{R}</m></em>. <idx><h>outer measure</h><h>Lebesgue outer measure</h></idx> 
    We will see (much!) more on this later.</p>
</example>
<p>Having constructed an outer measure from an arbitrary (set) function, we will now restrict outer measures to measures.</p>
<definition>
<p><idx><h>measurable set</h><h>with respect to an outer measure</h></idx>
    Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set and let <m>\mu^*</m> be an outer measure on <m>X</m>.
    A set <m>E \subseteq X</m> is <em>measurable with respect to <m>\mu^*</m></em> if</p>
<md> \mu^*(A) = \mu^*(A\cap E) + \mu^*(A\cap E^c),</md>
<p>for all <m>A \subseteq X.</m></p>
<p>The term <em><m>\mu^*</m>-measurable</em> is also used for sets which are measurable with respect to <m>\mu^*</m>.</p>
</definition>
<theorem xml:id="thm-measure-space-from-outer-measure">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set, let <m>\mu^*</m> be an outer measure on <m>X</m>, and let <m>\mathcal{M}</m> be the collection of all subsets of <m>X</m> which are measurable with respect to <m>\mu^*</m>.
    Then <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra and the restriction of <m>\mu^*</m> to <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is a measure.
    That is, <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a measure space, where <m>\mu = \mu^*|_\mathcal{M}</m>.
    Further, <m>(X,\mathcal{M},\mu)</m> is a complete measure space.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Clearly <m>\emptyset \in \mathcal{M}</m>.
    Also, if <m>E</m> is measurable with respect to <m>\mu^*</m>, then <m>E^c</m> is also in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
    To show that <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra it remains to show that <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under countable unions.
    We will do this in tandem with showing that <m>\mu^*|_\mathcal{M}</m> is a measure.</p>
<p>Let <m>E_1</m> and <m>E_2</m> be two <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable sets.
    Take any <m>A \subseteq X</m>.
    Then, since <m>E_1</m> and <m>E_2</m> are measurable, we have</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A)  = &amp;\mu^*(A \cap E_1) + \mu^*(A \cap E_1^c) \\
        = &amp; \mu^*(A \cap E_1) + \mu^*((A \cap E_1^c) \cap E_2) + \mu^*((A \cap E_1^c) \cap E_2^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Note that</p>
<md> [A\cap E_1] \cup [(A\cap E_1^c)\cap E_2] = A\cap (E_1 \cup E_2),</md>
<p>and</p>
<md> A \cap E_1^c \cap E_2^c = A \cap (E_1 \cup E_2)^c.</md>
<p>Hence</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A)  = &amp;\mu^*(A \cap E_1) + \mu^*(A \cap E_1^c) \\
        = &amp; \mu^*(A \cap E_1) + \mu^*((A \cap E_1^c) \cap E_2) + \mu^*((A \cap E_1^c) \cap E_2^c)\\
        \geq &amp; \mu^*(A\cap (E_1 \cup E_2)) + \mu^*(A \cap (E_1 \cup E_2)^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Therefore, <m>E_1\cup E_2</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.
    It follows inductively that if <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> is a finite collection of measurable sets, then <m>\bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k</m> is measurable.</p>
<p>Let <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> be a finite collection of disjoint measurable sets.
    Take any set <m>A \subseteq X</m>.
    Since the sets <m>\{E_k\}_k</m> are disjoint and measurable, we have</p>
<md number="yes" xml:id="eq-fin-count">
&lt;md&gt;
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A) &amp;= \mu^*(A\cap E_1) + \mu^*(A \cap E_1^c)\\
        &amp;= \mu^*((A\cap E_1) + \mu^*(A \cap E_2) + \mu^*(A \cap (E_1 \cup E_2)^c) \\
        &amp;\vdots \\
        &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(A \cap E_k) + \mu^*\left( A \cap \left(\bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k\right)^c\right).
\end{aligned}
&lt;/md&gt;
</md>
<p>In particular,</p>
<md> \mu^*\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k\right) = \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(E_k).</md>
<p>Thus far, we have shown that <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under finite unions, and <m>\mu^*</m> is additive on <em>finite</em> collections of disjoint sets in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
    As <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is closed under taking complements, it follows that <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is also closed under finite intersections.
    We need to extend finite to <em>infinite</em> in both instances.
    Let <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a countable collection of measurable sets and let <m>E = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k.</m>
    We will use our favorite trick to <q>disjointize</q> this collection.
    Though we have used this method before, we will go through the steps carefully to make sure that at each step we remain with a set in <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
    Let <m>F_1 = E_1</m>, and <m>F_2 = E_2 \backslash F_1</m>.
    Note that <m>E_2 \backslash F_1= E_2 \cap F_1^c \in \mathcal{M}.</m>
    Continuing in this way, for each <m>n</m> let</p>
<md> F_n = E_n \backslash \bigcup_{k=1}^{n-1}F_k.</md>
<p>Again, we have that <m>F_n \in \mathcal{M}</m> for each <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
    Thus <m>\{F_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is a countable collection of disjoint measurable sets.
    Further <m>\bigcup_{k=1}^n F_k = \bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k</m> for <m>n \in \mathbb{N} \cup\{\infty\}</m>.</p>
<p>Fix <m>n</m>, and take any <m>A \subseteq X</m>.
    Let <m>B = \bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k</m>.
    Then, by the measurability of <m>B</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A) = &amp; \mu^*(A \cap B) + \mu^*(A\cap B^c)\\
        =&amp; \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(A\cap F_k) + \mu^*(A\cap B^c)\\
        \geq&amp; \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(A\cap F_k) + \mu^*(A\cap E^c),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>where the second inequality comes from  <xref ref="eq-fin-count" text="Equation"/> and the last inequality holds since <m>B \subseteq E</m>.
    As this holds for all <m>n</m>, the countable monotonicity of the outer measure <m>\mu^*</m> gives</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(A)  \geq &amp; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(A\cap F_k) + \mu^*(A\cap E^c)\\
        \geq &amp; \mu^*(A\cap E) + \mu^*(A \cap E^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>It follows that <m>E</m> is measurable.</p>
<p>We have thus shown that <m>\mathcal{M}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.
    It remains to complete the proof that <m>\mu^*</m> is a measure when restricted to <m>\mathcal{M}</m>.
    It only remains to show that <m>\mu^*</m> is countably additive on disjoint measurable sets.
    Let <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> be a disjoint collection of measurable sets and let <m>E = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k</m>.
    If <m>\mu^*(E) = \infty</m>, then</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) \geq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(E_k),</md>
<p>and so <m>\mu^*(E) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(E_k)</m>.
    Suppose now that <m>\mu^*(E) &lt; \infty</m>.
    For every <m>n</m> we have, by the measurability of <m>E</m> and the finite additivity of <m>\mu^*</m> on disjoint sets,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(E) = \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(E_k) + \mu^*\left(E \backslash \bigcup_{k=n+1}^\infty E_k \right) \\
        \geq \sum_{k=1}^n \mu^*(E_k).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>n</m>, we have that <m>\mu^*(E) \geq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(E_k)</m>.
    Hence <m>\mu^*(E) = \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu^*(E_k)</m>.
    Thus <m>(X, \mathcal{M}, \mu^*|_\mathcal{M})</m> is a measure space.
    That this measure space is complete is left as an exercise (<xref ref="exer-zero-measurable" text="Exercise"/>).</p>
</proof>
<p>Starting we a function <m>\mu_0</m> on some set <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> we can now construct a measure.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Start with <m>\mu_0</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer-measure induced by <m>\mu_0</m> (<xref ref="thm-outer-measure" text="Theorem"/>);</p>
</li>
<li><p>let <m>\mu</m> be the measure we get by restricting <m>\mu^*</m> to the <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable sets (<xref ref="thm-measure-space-from-outer-measure" text="Theorem"/>).</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>We call <m>\mu</m> the <em>Carathéodory measure</em> induced by <m>\mu_0</m>.<idx><h>measure</h><h>Carathéodory measure</h></idx></p>
<p>Now that we can construct the Carathéodory measure <m>\mu</m> induced by a set function <m>\mu_0 \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m>, we can ask how <m>\mu_0</m> and <m>\mu</m> relate. In particular, when are we guaranteed that each set <m>A \in \mathcal{S}</m> is measurable with respect to <m>\mu</m>? And if the sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> are measurable, is <m>\mu|_{\mathcal{S}} = \mu_0</m>? As stated earlier, the answers to these questions rely both on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> and <m>\mu_0</m>.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set and let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a non-empty collection of subsets of <m>X</m>.
    A function <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> is a <em>premeasure</em><idx><h>premeasure</h></idx> if</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>\mu</m> is finitely additive, i.e. if <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> is a disjoint collection of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> whose union is also in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, then <m>\mu\left(\bigcup_{k=1}^n E_k\right) = \sum_{k=1}^n \mu(E_k)</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>\mu</m> is countably monotone, i.e. if <m>E,\ \{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> and <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_k E_k</m>, then <m>\mu(E) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k)</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\emptyset \in S</m>, then <m>\mu(\emptyset) =0</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</definition>
<p>Let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m>. As any measure is a premeasure, in necessary condition for the Carathéodory measure induced by <m>\mu</m> to agree with <m>\mu</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is for <m>\mu</m> to be a premeasure. With some additional structure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, we can show that the Carathéodory measure is an extension of a premeasure. When this happens, we call the Carathéodory measure a <em>Carathéodory extension</em>.<idx><h>Carathéodory extension</h></idx><fn>It may be the case that there are more measures than the Carathéodory extension which extend a premeasure <m>\mu</m>. However, we will see in <xref ref="thm-Car-ext-1" text="Theorem"/> that Carathéodory is sometimes unique.</fn></p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Car-ext-1">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set.
    Let <m>\mathcal{S} \subseteq \mathcal{P}(X)</m> be a non-empty collection of subseteq which is closed under relative complements<idx><h>relative complement</h></idx>. That is, if <m>A,B \in \mathcal{S}</m>, then <m>A \backslash B \in \mathcal{S}</m>.
    Let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> be a premeasure, and let <m>\overline{\mu}</m> be the Carathéodory measure induced by <m>\mu</m>.
    Then each <m>A \in \mathcal{S}</m> is <m>\overline{\mu}</m>-measurable, and <m>\overline{\mu}(A) = \mu(A)</m>.
    That is, <m>\overline{\mu}</m> is the Carathéodory extenion on <m>\mu</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>Take <m>A \in \mathcal{S}</m>.
We will show that <m>A</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable, where <m>\mu^*</m> is the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>.
Take any <m>E \in X</m>.
We need to show that</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) = \mu^*(E\cap A) + \mu^*(E \cap A^c).</md>
<p>If <m>\mu^*(E) = \infty</m> then this equality clearly holds.
Thus we will suppose that <m>\mu^*(E) &lt; \infty.</m>
It suffices to show that</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) = \mu^*(E\cap A) + \mu^*(E \cap A^c).</md>
<p>Fix a <m>\varepsilon &gt; 0</m>.
By the definition of <m>\mu^*</m>, and since <m>\mu^*(E)&lt;\infty</m>, there exists a countable collection <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k</m> and</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) + \varepsilon \geq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k).</md>
<p>Note that, <m>E_k \cap A = E_k \backslash [E_k\backslash A]</m>, and hence <m>E_k \cap A \in \mathcal{S}</m> for each <m>k</m>.
Further, <m>E_k \cap A^c = E_k \backslash A</m>, and so <m>E \cap A^c \in \mathcal{S}</m> for each <m>k</m>.
By the countable additivity of <m>\mu</m> we thus have</p>
<md> \mu(E_k) = \mu(E_k \cap A) + \mu(E_k \cap A^c).</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md> \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k) =\sum_{k=1}^\infty (\mu(E_k \cap A) + \mu(E_k \cap A^c)).</md>
<p>As <m>\{E_k \cap A\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> covers <m>E \cap A</m> and <m>\{E_k \cap A^c\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> covers <m>E \cap A^c</m> we have that</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k\cap A) &amp;\geq \mu^*(E\cap A) \text{ and}\\
    \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k\cap A^c) &amp;\geq \mu^*(E\cap A^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Thus</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(E) + \varepsilon &amp;\geq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k) \\
    &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k \cap A) + \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k \cap A^c) \\
    &amp;\geq \mu^*(E\cap A) + \mu^*(E \cap A^c).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>\varepsilon &gt;0</m>, it follows that</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) = \mu^*(E\cap A) + \mu^*(E \cap A^c).</md>
<p>Thus <m>A</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.</p>
<p>That <m>\mu^*(E)=\mu(E)</m> for all <m>E \in \mathcal{S}</m> follows since <m>\mu</m> is countably monotone.
Thus the Carathéodory measure induced by <m>\mu</m> is an extension of <m>\mu</m>.</p>
</proof>
<p>The conditions on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> in <xref ref="thm-Car-ext-1" text="Theorem"/> are not quite what we will have practical use for. We instead will look at <em>semirings of subsets</em>.</p>
<definition>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set and let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be a non-empty collection of subsets of <m>X</m>.
The collection <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a <em>semiring</em> (of subsets of <m>X</m>)<idx><h>semiring</h></idx> if for each <m>A,B \in \mathcal{S}</m></p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>A \cap B \in \mathcal{S}</m>; and</p>
</li>
<li><p>there exists a finite disjoint collection <m>\{C_k\}_{k=1}^n</m> of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> such that
    <md> A \backslash B = \bigcup_{k=1}^n C_k.</md>
</p>
</li>
</ol>
</definition>
<p>Note that if <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, then <m>\emptyset \in \mathcal{S}</m>. Indeed, if <m>A \in \mathcal{S}</m> then <m>\emptyset = A \backslash A</m> can be written as a disjoint union of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>. These sets are necessarily the empty set.</p>
<example xml:id="exam-interval-semiring">
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{I}_1</m> be the collection of all intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>; let <m>\mathcal{I}_2</m> be the collection of all intervals of finite length in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>; and let <m>\mathcal{I}_3</m> be the collection of intervals of the form</p>
<md> \mathcal{I}_3 = \{ (a,b] \colon a \leq b\}.</md>
<p>Then each of <m>\mathcal{I}_1</m>, <m>\mathcal{I}_2</m>, and <m>\mathcal{I}_3</m> are semirings of subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</example>
<example xml:id="exam-product-semiring">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{M}, \mu)</m> and <m>(Y, \mathcal{N}, \nu)</m> be two measure spaces.
Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of subsets of <m>X \times Y</m> given by</p>
<md> \mathcal{S} = \{ A \times B \colon A \in \mathcal{M}, \ B \in \mathcal{N}\}.</md>
<p>Then <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring.
The elements of <m>\mathcal{S}</m> are called <em>measurable rectangles.</em><idx><h>measurable rectangle</h></idx>
More on this later, when we look at product measures.</p>
</example>
<lemma xml:id="lem-Car-ext-2">
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be a semiring of subsets of a non-empty subset <m>X</m>
and let</p>
<md> \mathcal{S}' = \left\{ \bigcup_{k=1}^n C_k : \{C_k\}_{k=1}^n \text{ finite disjoint collection in }\mathcal{S}\right\}.</md>
<p>Then <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is closed under relative complements.
Further, if <m>\mu</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> then <m>\mu</m> extends uniquely to a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.</p>
</lemma>
<proof>
<p>Note that <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is closed under finite intersections.
It follows that <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is also closed under finite intersections.
Now take <m>A, B \in \mathcal{S}</m>.
We can write <m>A \cup B</m> as the disjoint union</p>
<md> A \cup B = (A \backslash B) \cup (A\cap B) \cup (B\backslash A).</md>
<p>As each of the three terms can be written as disjoint unions of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, it follows that <m>A \cup B \in \mathcal{S}'</m>.
Inductively, it can be shown that <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is closed under finite unions.</p>
<p>Let <m>\{A_i\}_{i=1}^m</m> and <m>\{B_j\}_{j=1}^n</m> be finite disjoint collections of sets from <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
We have that</p>
<md> \left[ \bigcup_{i=1}^m A_i \right] \backslash \left[ \bigcup_{j=1}^n B_j \right]
 = \bigcup_{j=1}^m \left[ \bigcap_{i=1}^n (A_i \backslash B_j) \right].</md>
<p>Thus, relative complements of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> can be written as finite unions of finite intersections of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.
As <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is closed under finite unions and finite intersections, it follows that <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is closed under relative complements.</p>
<p>Suppose now that <m>\mu</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
For disjoint sets <m>\{A_i\}_{i=1}^m</m> in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> define</p>
<md> \mu'\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^m A_i\right) = \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(A_i).</md>
<p>We must first show that <m>\mu'</m> is well-defined on <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.
To this end, suppose <m>\{A_i\}_{i=1}^m</m> and <m>\{B_j\}_{j=1}^n</m> are finite disjoint collections in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> with <m>\bigcup_{i=1}^m A_i = \bigcup_{j=1}^n B_j</m>.
Note that, for each <m>j</m>, <m>B_j = \bigcup_{i=1}^m (B_j \cap A_i)</m>  is a disjoint union of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
By the finite additivity of <m>\mu</m>,</p>
<md> \mu(B_j) = \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(B_j \cap A_i).</md>
<p>Similarly, for each <m>i</m>,</p>
<md> \mu(A_i) = \sum_{j=1}^n (B_j \cap A_i).</md>
<p>Thus,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\sum_{j=1}^n \mu(B_j) &amp;= \sum_{j=1}^n \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(B_j \cap A_i) \\
 &amp;= \sum_{i=1}^m \sum_{j=1}^n \mu(B_j \cap A_i) \\
 &amp;= \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(A_i).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu'</m> is a well-defined function on <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.</p>
<p>That <m>\mu'</m> is finitely additive is clear.
To show that <m>\mu'</m> is a premeasure, it remains to show countable monotonicity.
To this end, take a countable collection <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> in <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>, and <m>E \in \mathcal{S}'</m> such that</p>
<md> E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k.</md>
<p>Note that, since <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> is closed under finite unions and relative complements, we can assume that the collection <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> is disjoint.
As sets in <m>\mathcal{S}'</m> are disjoint unions of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, can further assume that the sets <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
Let <m>\{A_i\}_{i=1}^m</m> be disjoint sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> such that <m>E = \bigcup_{i=1}^m A_i</m>.
By the countable monotonicity of <m>\mu</m> we have</p>
<md> \mu(A_i) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(A_i \cap E_k)</md>
<p>for each <m>1\leq i \leq m</m>.
Hence</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu'(E) &amp; = \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(A_i) \\
    &amp;\leq  \sum_{i=1}^m\sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(A_i \cap E_k)\\
    &amp;=  \sum_{k=1}^\infty \sum_{i=1}^m \mu(A_i \cap E_k)\\
    &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E \cap E_k) \\
    &amp;\leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu'(E_k).
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>Hence <m>\mu'</m> is a premeasure on <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.</p>
<p>The uniqueness of <m>\mu'</m> follows from the definition of <m>\mathcal{S}'</m>.</p>
</proof>
<p>Let <m>\mu_0</m> be a function on a collection of subsets <m>\mathcal{S}</m> of <m>X</m>. Denote by <m>\mathcal{S}_\sigma</m> the collection of all countable unions of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>; and denote by <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> the collection of all countable intersections of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}_\sigma</m>. Note that, if the sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> are measurable with respect to the Carathéodory measure <m>\mu</m> induced by <m>\mu_0</m> (in particular, if <m>\mu</m> is an extension of <m>\mu_0</m>), then the sets in <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> are also measurable. The following proposition tells us that the sets in <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> can often be used to approximate the outer measure <m>\mu^*</m> (and indeed the measure <m>\mu</m>).</p>
<remark>
<p>The <m>\sigma\delta</m>-notation used above is supposed to be reminiscent of <m>G_\sigma</m> and <m>F_\delta</m> notation used in topology: <m>G_\sigma</m>-sets are countable unions of open sets; <m>F_\delta</m>-sets are countable intersections of closed sets.<fn>`G' for `open' comes from the German word geöffnet; `F' for `closed' comes from the French word fermé.</fn>
    When working with measures on topological spaces we will often use <m>G_\delta</m> and <m>F_\sigma</m> sets in the way <m>S_{\sigma\delta}</m> sets are used in the following proposition.</p>
</remark>
<proposition xml:id="prop-sigma-delta-sets">
<p>Let <m>\mu</m> be a set function on a collection <m>\mathcal{S}</m> of subsets of <m>X</m>, and let <m>\mu^*</m> be the induced outer measure, and let <m>\mu</m> be the induced Carathéodory measure.</p>
<p>If <m>E \subseteq X</m> satisfies <m>\mu^*(E)&lt;\infty</m> then there exists an <m>A \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> such that <m>E \subseteq A</m> and <m>\mu^*(E) = \mu^*(A)</m>.
    If <m>E</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable and each set in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable, then <m>A</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable and <m>\mu(A \backslash E) = 0</m>.</p>
</proposition>
<proof>
<p>Suppose <m>\mu^*(E) &lt; \infty</m>. 
By the definition of <m>\mu^*</m>, for each <m>n</m> there exists a countable collection <m>\{E_{n,k}\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_{n,k}</m> and</p>
<md> \mu^*(E) + \frac{1}{n} &gt; \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_{n,k}).</md>
<p>Let <m>A_n = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_{n,k}</m>.
Then <m>A_n \in \mathcal{S}_\sigma</m> and</p>
<md> \mu^*(A_n) \leq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E_k) &lt; \mu^*(E) + \frac{1}{n}.</md>
<p>Now let <m>A = \bigcap_{n=1}^\infty A_n</m>.
Then <m>A \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m>, and <m>E \subseteq A</m>.
Further, for each <m>n</m>,</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\mu^*(E) &amp;\leq \mu^*(A) \\
    &amp;\leq \mu^*(A_n) \\
    &amp;&lt; \mu^*(E) + \frac{1}{n}.
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>As this holds for all <m>n</m>, it follows that <m>\mu^*(E) = \mu^*(A)</m>.</p>
<p>Finally, if <m>\mu</m> extends <m>\mu_0</m> then every set in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is measurable, and thus every set in <m>\mathcal{S}_\sigma</m> and <m>\mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> is measurable.
If <m>E</m> is also measurable, then by the excision property</p>
<md> \mu(E\backslash A) = \mu(E) - \mu(A) = 0.</md>
<p>\qedhere</p>
</proof>
<p>We are now ready for the main theorem of this section: our main tool for constructing measures. The uniqueness in the following theorem is important and will be used frequently. Before stating the theorem we need one more definition. If <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a collection of subsets of <m>X</m>, and <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty]</m> is a function, we say that <m>\mu</m> is <em><m>\sigma</m>-finite</em><idx><h sortby="sigma-finite set function"><m>\sigma</m>-finite set function</h></idx>if there is a countable collection <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> with <m>\mu(E_k)&lt; \infty</m> for all <m>k</m>, and <m>X = \bigcup_{k=1}^\infty E_k</m>. Note that this definition is consistent with the definition of a <m>\sigma</m>-finite measure.</p>
<theorem xml:id="thm-Car-ext-2">
<title>Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem</title>
<p><idx><h>Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem</h></idx><idx><h>Carathéodory extension</h></idx>
Let <m>\mu_0</m> be a premeasure on a semiring <m>\mathcal{S}</m> of subsets of a non-empty set <m>X</m>.
Then the Carathéodory measure <m>\mu</m> induced by <m>\mu_0</m> is an extension of <m>\mu_0</m>.
Furthermore, if <m>\mu_0</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite and <m>\mu</m> is the unique measure on the set of <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable subsets extending <m>\mu_0</m>.</p>
</theorem>
<proof>
<p>That <m>\mu</m> extends <m>\mu_0</m> follows from <xref ref="thm-Car-ext-1" text="Theorem"/> and <xref ref="lem-Car-ext-2" text="Lemma"/>.
    If <m>\mu_0</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, then <m>\mu</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite since <m>\mu</m> extends <m>\mu_0</m>.</p>
<p>It remains to show that <m>\mu</m> is unique when <m>\mu_0</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite.
    Suppose that <m>\nu</m> is another measure on the <m>\mu</m>-measurable sets which extends <m>u_0</m>.
    Suppose <m>E \in X</m> satisfies <m>\mu^*(E) = 0</m>.
    By the definition of the out measure <m>\mu^*</m>, if we fix <m>\varepsilon&gt;0</m> there exists <m>\{E_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> such that <m>E \subseteq \bigcup_k E_k</m> and</p>
<md> \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu_0(E_k) &lt; \varepsilon.</md>
<p>Noting that <m>\mu_0(E_k) = \nu(E_k)</m> for each <m>k</m>, the countable monotonicity of <m>\nu</m> implies that <m>\nu(E) = 0</m>.</p>
<p>Take any <m>A \in \mathcal{S}_\sigma</m> (i.e. <m>A</m> is a countable union of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>).
    As <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring, we can write <m>A</m> as a disjoint countable union of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
    Since <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m> are countably additive and agree on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, it follows that <m>\mu(A) = \nu(A)</m>.
    If <m>A \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> (i.e. <m>A</m> is a countable intersection of sets in <m>\mathcal{S}_\sigma</m>), and <m>\mu(A)&lt; \infty</m>, then by the continuity of measure, for both <m>\mu</m> and <m>\nu</m>, we have that <m>\mu(A) = \nu(A)</m>.</p>
<p>Now take <m>E_0 \in \mathcal{S}</m> with <m>\mu_0(E_0)&lt;\infty</m>.
    Take any <m>E \subseteq E_0</m>. We will show that <m>\mu(E) = \nu(E)</m>.
    By <xref ref="prop-sigma-delta-sets" text="Proposition"/>, there is an <m>A \in \mathcal{S}_{\sigma\delta}</m> such that <m>E\subseteq A</m> and <m>\mu(A\backslash E) = 0</m>.
    We can further assume that <m>A \subseteq E_0</m>.
    By the excision property</p>
<md> \nu(E) = \nu(A) - \nu(A\backslash E).</md>
<p>We have already shown that <m>\nu(A) = \mu(A)</m> and <m>\nu(A \backslash E) = \mu(A\backslash E)</m>. And hence <m>\nu(E) = \mu(A)</m>.</p>
<p>Finally, if <m>\mu_0</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite, there are sets <m>\{X_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> in <m>\mathcal{S}</m> which cover all of <m>X</m> and satisfy <m>\mu_0(X_k)&lt;\infty</m>.
    We can further assume that the sets <m>\{X_k\}_{k=1}^\infty</m> are disjoint. 
    Thus, if <m>E \subseteq X</m> is measurable then</p>
<md>
\begin{aligned}
\nu(E) &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \nu(E \cap X_k) \\
        &amp;= \sum_{k=1}^\infty \mu(E \cap X_k) \\
        &amp;= \mu(E),
\end{aligned}
</md>
<p>thus proving the uniqueness of <m>\mu</m>.</p>
</proof>
</section>
<exercises>
<exercise xml:id="exer-cocount-measure">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be an uncountable set.
A set <m>A \subseteq X</m> is <em>cocountable</em> if its complement <m>A^c</m> is countable.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that the collection <m>\mathcal{M}</m> of all subsets of <m>X</m> which are either countable or cocountable forms a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.<idx><h sortby="sigma-algebra"><m>\sigma</m>-algebra</h><h>countable-cocountable <m>\sigma</m>-algebra</h></idx></p>
</li>
<li><p>Define a function <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{M} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> by <m>\mu(A) = 0</m> if <m>A</m> is countable, and <m>\mu(A) = 1</m> if <m>A</m> is cocountable. Show that <m>\mu</m> is a measure.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Prove the claims in <xref ref="exam-counting" text="Example"/>.
That is, show that the counting measure<idx><h>measure</h><h>counting measure</h></idx> <m>c</m> on a non-empty set <m>X</m> defines a complete measure.</p>
<p>Show that <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X),c)</m> is <m>\sigma</m>-finite if and only if <m>X</m> is countable.
Show that <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X),c)</m> is a finite measure space if and only if <m>X</m> is finite.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-counting-Borel">
<p>Let <m>X</m> be a non-empty set with the discrete topology. Let <m>c</m> be the counting measure on <m>(X,\mathcal{P}(X))</m>.
    Show that <m>c</m> is a Borel measure.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-dirac-meas">
<p>Let <m>(X,\mathcal{F})</m> be a measurable space.
Fix <m>x \in X</m>, and let <m>\delta_x</m> be the Dirac measure defined in <xref ref="exam-dirac-measure" text="Example"/>.
Show that <m>\delta_x</m> is a measure.</p>
<p>Suppose <m>X</m> is a topological space, and <m>\mathcal{F} = \mathcal{B}(X)</m> is the Borel sets. Show that <m>\delta_x</m> is a Borel measure.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-borel-on-extended">
<p><idx><h>Borel sets</h><h>in the extended real line</h></idx><idx><h>extended real line</h></idx>
    Let <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}} = \mathbb{R}\cup \{-\infty, \infty\}</m> be the extended real line.
    Let <m>\overline{\mathcal{B}}</m> be the collection of sets in <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}}</m> given by</p>
<md> \overline{\mathcal{B}} = \{ A \subseteq \overline{\mathbb{R}} \colon A \cap \mathbb{R} \in \mathcal{B}\},</md>
<p>where <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is the collection of Borel sets in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
    Show that <m>\overline{\mathcal{B}}</m> is a <m>\sigma</m>-algebra.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-top-on-extended">
<p>Let <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}} = \{-\infty, \infty\}</m> be the extended real line.<idx><h>extended real line</h></idx>
For <m>U \subseteq \overline{\mathbb{R}}</m> we say <m>U</m> is <em>open in <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}}</m></em> if it satisfies the following conditions</p>
<ol>
<li><p><m>U \cap \mathbb{R}</m>  is open in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p>if <m>\infty \in U</m>, then there exists <m>n \in \mathbb{R}</m> such that <m>(n,\infty) \subseteq U</m>;</p>
</li>
<li><p><m>-\infty \in U</m>, then there exists <m>n \in \mathbb{R}</m> such that <m>(-\infty,n) \subseteq U</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Show that this defines a topology on <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}}</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-borel-on-extended-2">
<p>Let <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}} = \{-\infty, \infty\}</m>.<idx><h>extended real line</h></idx>
Let <m>\overline{\mathcal{B}}</m> be the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra from <xref ref="exer-borel-on-extended" text="Exercise"/>.
Endow <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}}</m> with the topology from <xref ref="exer-top-on-extended" text="Exercise"/>.
Show that the <m>\sigma</m>-algebra of Borel sets in <m>\overline{\mathbb{R}}</m>, <m>\mathcal{B}(\overline{\mathbb{R}})</m>, conincides with <m>\overline{\mathcal{B}}</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Prove <xref ref="thm-completion-of-meas-space" text="Theorem"/>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Let <m>(Y,\mathcal{F},\mu)</m> be a measure space, and let <m>(Z,\mathcal{G})</m> be a measurable space.
Let <m>f \colon Y \rightarrow Z</m> be a  function satisfying <m>f^{-1}(B) \in \mathcal{F}</m> for all <m>B \in \mathcal{G}</m>.
Define a function <m>f_*\mu</m> on <m>\mathcal{G}</m> by</p>
<md>f_*\mu(A) = \mu(f^{-1}(A)).</md>
<ol>
<li><p>Show that <m>f_*\mu</m> is a measure on <m>(Z,\mathcal{G})</m>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>Show that <m>\mu(Y) = f_*\mu(Y)</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-induced-counting-outer-measure">
<p>Prove the claim in <xref ref="ex-induced-counting-outer-measure" text="Example"/>:
    Let <m>X</m> be an infinite set, and let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all finite subsets of <m>X</m>.
    Let <m>\mu \colon \mathcal{S} \rightarrow [0,\infty)</m> be the counting function.
    Let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>. Show that <m>\mu^*=c</m>, the counting measure on <m>X</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-induced-length-outer-measure">
<p>Prove the claim in <xref ref="ex-induced-length-outer-measure" text="Example"/>:
    Let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all open intervals in the real line.
    Let <m>\mu</m> be the length function on <m>\mathcal{S}</m>, i.e. <m>\mu(I) = \ell(I)</m> for all <m>I \in \mathcal{S}</m>.
    Let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>. 
    Show that <m>\mu^*(I) = \ell(I)</m> for all intervals <m>I</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-zero-measurable">
<p>Let <m>\mu^*</m> be an outer measure on a non-empty set <m>X</m>.
    Show that if <m>\mu^*(A) = 0</m> then <m>A</m> is <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.
    (Note that this completes the proof of <xref ref="thm-measure-space-from-outer-measure" text="Theorem"/>).</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-interval-semiring">
<p>Show that the collections <m>\mathcal{I}_1</m>, <m>\mathcal{I}_2</m> and <m>\mathcal{I}_3</m> from <xref ref="exam-interval-semiring" text="Example"/> form a semirings of subsets of <m>\mathbb{R}</m>.
    That is show that the collection <m>\mathcal{I}_1</m> of all intervals in <m>\mathbb{R}</m>; the colletion <m>\mathcal{I}_2</m> of all intervals of finite length; and <m>\mathcal{I}_3</m> of all intervals of the form <m>(a,b]</m>, <m>a\leq b</m>, for semirings.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-product-semiring">
<p><idx><h>measurable rectangle</h></idx>
Show that the collection <m>\mathcal{S}</m> from <xref ref="exam-product-semiring" text="Example"/> forms a semiring.
That is, if <m>(X,\mathcal{M}, \mu)</m> and <m>(Y, \mathcal{N}, \nu)</m> are two measure spaces and</p>
<md> \mathcal{S} = \{ A \times B \colon A \in \mathcal{M}, \ B \in \mathcal{N}\},</md>
<p>show that <m>\mathcal{S}</m> is a semiring of subsets of <m>X \times Y</m>.</p>
</exercise>
<exercise>
<p>Let <m>X</m> be an uncountable set and let <m>\mathcal{S}</m> be the collection of all countable subsets of <m>\mathcal{S}</m>.
    Define a function <m>\mu</m> on <m>\mathcal{S}</m> by <m>\mu(A) = 0</m> for all <m>A \subseteq \mathcal{S}</m>.
    Let <m>\mu^*</m> be the outer measure induced by <m>\mu</m>.
    Determine <m>\mu^*</m> for each <m>A \subseteq X</m>.
    Determine which sets are <m>\mu^*</m>-measurable.
    Note that the <m>0</m> measure <m>\nu(A) = 0</m> for all <m>A \subseteq X</m> is also an extension of <m>\mu</m>.
    Why does this not contradict the Carathéodory-Hahn Theorem (<xref ref="thm-Car-ext-2" text="Theorem"/>)?</p>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="exer-length-premeasure">
<p>Let <m>\mathcal{I}_1</m>, <m>\mathcal{I}_2</m> and <m>\mathcal{I}_3</m> be the semirings of intervals from <xref ref="exer-interval-semiring" text="Exercise"/>.
    Show that the length function <m>\ell</m> when restricted to each <m>\mathcal{I}_i</m> is a premeasure of <m>\mathcal{I}_i</m>, for <m>i=1,2,3</m>.</p>
</exercise>
</exercises>
</chapter>
